# TS Express layering

## Rule
Node/TS Express layers: `route → middleware → controller → service → repository / proxy`. All routes register in `src/routes.ts`. Repositories extend `BaseRepository`; outbound clients extend `BaseProxy` (Axios).

## Why
`admin-backend`'s `coding-guidelines.md` mandates this structure. Scattered route registration across feature folders has previously caused forgotten middleware.

## Constraints
- Every route is added to `src/routes.ts`; no ad hoc `app.get(...)` elsewhere.
- `auditLogger` middleware wraps mutating routes; `checkPermission` wraps role-gated routes.
- Repositories extend `BaseRepository<TModel>`; outbound HTTP clients extend `BaseProxy`.
- Handlers read from AJV-validated DTOs (`json-schema-validation` rule); services never see raw `req.body`.
- Controllers translate typed errors to envelopes via the central error middleware (`typed-error-handling`).

## Examples

### Good
```ts
// src/routes.ts
router.post('/ports', auditLogger, checkPermission('MASTER_DATA_WRITE'), validate(PortSchema), PortController.create);

// controller
class PortController {
  static create = async (req, res, next) => {
    try { const p = await PortService.create(req.validated); res.status(201).json(p); }
    catch (e) { next(e); }
  };
}
```

### Bad
```ts
// Route defined inside a feature file, middleware skipped
app.post('/ports', async (req, res) => { await repo.insertOne(req.body); res.json(...); });
```

